## Hi

Welcome to your new project. We're glad you're here!

I've compiled this handover plan to help you get up to speed in your new role. Feel free to reach out if you have any questions 

## Guiding thoughts

Starting a new project can be overwhelming, so here are some guiding thoughts to integrate smoothly and feel comfortable in your new project

ng, so here are some guiding thoughts to integrate smoothly and feel comfortable in your new project

- Take time to learn. Don't get sucked into the minutia of decision-making or project involvement too early - there will be plenty of time for that later. In your handover process, focus on getting comfortable and learning how things work.
- Don't be afraid to ask. No one expects you to know how things at the project work right away. Take advantage of that and ask for help when you need it.
- Be Proactive: If you see areas that could be improved, suggest constructive changes. Fresh perspectives are often valuable for continuous improvements.
- Stay Organized: Make sure you follow the handover steps in a planned manner and complete all items.

## Flow

- The customer sends daily data to invent-liwa-input-dev container in Microsoft Azure Storage every night at 3.30 AM.
- Daily dag starts running at 3.15 AM - the client is not providing a manifest file. The daily dag will move on to other tasks as soon as there is the new input file directory with date and timestamp.
- All files are pushed at once so there is no partial upload of the files.
- We receive a total of 31 files in the daily flow. All of these are listed in the pre-ETL sheet. Azure location: inventliwashared/invent-liwa-input-dev/historypre_etl_codesNotebook for pre-etl checks
- Results are saved in the inventliwashared/invent-liwa-output-dev folder, from which the client retrieves the data. Outputs should be available no later than 6:15 AM TR time.
- If results are not delivered to the customer by 6:15 AM TR time, the below email is sent both to the customer and to us. (rpl_results_fail_mail)

by 6:15 AM TR time, the below email is sent both to the customer and to us. (rpl_results_fail_mail)

1. Check your mail box:  To access the logs page of a failed task, please use the provided Log link. This will directly take you to the logs page where you can find more information about the error. Please note that identifying the problem by looking at the logs may be difficult.In such cases, it is recommended to check the Databricks job run if the issue is not related to Databricks or airflow, or any other mechanical problem. By doing so, you can get a better understanding of the problem and find a suitable solution. If you already familiar with the error and you think there is no need to track, Mark success link leads you where you can mark the task as success in order to prevent all the other dags to be failed.

eads you where you can mark the task as success in order to prevent all the other dags to be failed.
2. Check cicd slack channel: To easily access the DAG  in case of Airflow errors, please check the CICD Slack channel. This is the most convenient way to find and resolve errors related to Airflow. By checking the CICD Slack channel, you can quickly identify the specific DAG where the error occurred and take necessary actions to resolve it.

3.   Find the failed task: If above two step does not give you an idea about the what may be the problem, go to the Airflow web interface and find the DAG that contains the failed task. Click on the DAG to view the DAG's graph view. Failed tasks will appear in red. Click on the failed task to see more information about the task's failure. Once you are here, you can click on See Databricks Job Runto directly see the logs of the task.

Check Task Logs

here, you can click on See Databricks Job Runto directly see the logs of the task.

Check Task Logs

Once you have identified the failed task, check the task logs to determine the cause of the failure. You can find the task logs by clicking on the failed task in the DAG graph view and then clicking on the Logs tab. Look for any error messages or stack traces that may provide clues to the cause of the failure. As stated earlier this can only give you an idea about if the task is failed due to a mechanical problem. In order to identify the real problem click on See Databricks Job Run.

The job run logs contain valuable information that can help us pinpoint the cause of the failure. The red part of the log indicates the exact point where the problem arose, step by step. The white part shows everything that happened until you reach that point.

When someone ask you send full trace of the log, send them standard error file or directly the job run link.Fix the Issue

send full trace of the log, send them standard error file or directly the job run link.Fix the Issue

Once you have identified the cause of the failure, fix the issue. Depending on the issue, there are different ways to fix the task. Here are some common fixes:

- Fixing a coding error: If the task failed due to a coding error, fix the error and re-run the task.
- Increasing resources: If the task failed due to insufficient resources, such as memory or CPU, increase the resources and re-run the task.
- Adjusting parameters: If the task failed due to incorrect parameters, adjust the parameters and re-run the task.

rameters: If the task failed due to incorrect parameters, adjust the parameters and re-run the task.

> Info: Error Sources: Development: Errors resulting from development work, and the development needs to be revised by going back to the source. Customer Data Related: Errors that occur when there is a lack of data, incorrect data, or missing data from the customer. Communication with the customer should be established to resolve the issue. Airflow: Errors related to Airflow, such as triggering of interconnected tasks or connection problems. The source of the error should be resolved and the task may need to be re-run if necessary. Timeout: Errors that occur when the specified time for triggering or waiting for a task is exceeded. The source of the error should be identified, and the task may need to be re-run.Delta Cache: Delete the required files and re-run

Retry the Task

and the task may need to be re-run.Delta Cache: Delete the required files and re-run

Retry the Task

Once you have fixed the issue, retry the task. You can retry the task by clicking on the failed task in the DAG graph view and then clicking on the Clear button to clear the task's state.

Once a task has been cleared and has started running, it will be displayed as an open green box. If the task completes successfully, it will be outlined in dark green.

If a cluster of tasks have completed successfully and you wish to rerun a failed task, clear the failed task.

The "Upstream" option selects all tasks upstream of the selected task, while the "Downstream" option selects all tasks downstream of the selected task.

Monitor the Task

After re-running the task, monitor the task to ensure that it completes successfully. You can monitor the task by clicking on the task in the DAG graph view and then clicking on the Graph View tab. The task's status will be displayed in the graph view.

view and then clicking on the Graph View tab. The task's status will be displayed in the graph view.

Log Task Failures to Google Sheets

When logging task failures, please make sure to include all relevant information such as the date and time of the failure, the name of the task that failed, and the reason for the failure. This will help to properly diagnose and troubleshoot any issues that arise. The direct link to the Google Sheet  bookmarked to cicd channel for easy access.

Main purpose of the task to calculate an average price of products for a specific period. Then, these average prices will be used in discount calculation. To see default parameters check relevant [noob config](https://github.com/inventanalytics/rocks-noob/blob/main/rocks/noob/config.yml) section and to see code script [noob asp](https://github.com/inventanalytics/rocks-noob/blob/main/rocks/noob/promotion/asp_calculation.py). The table below is a table resulting from the ASP calculation. It is calculated on a per product basis each day. A 15% change in ASP values results in the calculation of a new group_asp. Base_price is the max(group_asp) of the last 3 days

results in the calculation of a new group_asp. Base_price is the max(group_asp) of the last 3 days. base_price and group_asp do not change unless there is a 15% change in ASP.

- discount_calculation:

After gathering the average price of products(ASP), group_asp and base_price, this task used to decide if there is a promotion in a specific day. Then, a ratio is calculated to decide how much price is deviate from average price.

Above picture represents;

- at which level (groupby_cols: product_id) daily price will be compared
- to decide deviation will be divided into how many parts and what ratio will be borders. (borders)
- labeling those parts(labels)
- deciding which label will be considered as promotion (labels_that_are_promo)

g those parts(labels)
- deciding which label will be considered as promotion (labels_that_are_promo)

Discount Calculation checks whether there is a discount using the group_asp and base_price in the table below. If (base_price - group_asp)/base_price is within the discount rates specified in the config, it is assumed that there is a promotion on those days. # Noob Chain Level

Used for forecasting IA products whereas Noob Daily feeds into RPL and TRN runs.
Since IA pairs do not have historical sales data, results cannot be produced from Lltd. Therefore, an ML-based forecasting model (Prophet) is used. The model is not trained daily; once trained, the coefficients are used daily for predictions. The training is done on a notebook, while the prediction runs daily on a DAG.

- cl_in_season:

Flags whether a product is currently in season by analyzing its sales data.

- cl_weekly_enrich:

Similar to daily data but aggregated on a weekly basis. For more robust forecasts, both input and output (prediction) data are at a weekly level. This approach facilitates easier predictions for products with no historical sales data.

- cl_weekly_inventory:

Weekly inventory data used to create broken assortment data.

- cl_weekly_broken_assortment:

ntory:

- cl_weekly_broken_assortment:

- cl_weekly_lag_features:

Computes sales-related statistics (e.g., total sales, average sales) at different hierarchy levels (product or store) and various lag levels. This allows predictions to be made based on statistics that match the hierarchy of the new product. cl_weekly_lag_features identifies which features are used in the parameter given in the [config](https://github.com/inventanalytics/customer-pipeline-liwa/blob/main/rocks_extension/noob/config.yml).

- cl_weekly_sales_frequency:

Calculates sales frequency at different hierarchy levels for store and product.

- cl_weekly_seasonality_multiplier_features:

Previously, coefficients were calculated at the product-store level on a daily basis. These coefficients are now aggregated to hierarchy and weekly levels for use in CL.

### 1. Scope Selection

#### SP Link | SP Rules

- The reports and algorithms are run only for the active products. So, the products that have sales or inventory in the last 3 years are considered as active in the invent algorithms and reports.
- Products having total sales of 0 for the last 6 months will be out of scope for transfer optimization
- Options (M/Cs) with size-weighted warehouse inventory of greater than or equal to 30 will not be triggered for transfer runs. (This parameter can be changed in UI as well for default runs)
- Invent will maintain a higher percentage for bras (maybe with a different approach from the one explained above) as there are a greater number of sizes per line and majority of the demand is generated from a few sizes.

ere are a greater number of sizes per line and majority of the demand is generated from a few sizes.

### 1.1 Store Selection

#### SP Link | SP Rules

- Retail stores (owned by LIWA) will be in-scope.
- E-com will be out of scope.
- Stores having no sales for the last 3 weeks will be out-of-scope.
- Stores with sales start date within the last 15 days will be considered as new stores and will be blocked as source stores.

### 1.2 Pair (Product-Store) Selection for Transfer Runs & Reporting

#### SP Link | SP Rules

- Store-option pairs with positive inventory quantity in transit will be blocked as source.
- Freeze period for recently transferred products will be 21 days. This means that the transfer system will allow 21 days for the product transferred to the destination making sure that there will be at least 21 days in between two transfer movements for a specific product.
- Pairs that have their first inventory movements within the last 21 days will be blocked as source.

- Pairs that have their first inventory movements within the last 21 days will be blocked as source.

### 2.  Shipment Constraints / System Limitations

### 2.1 Broken Assortment (Size Distribution) Logic

#### SP Link | SP Rules

- Weights different sizes with respect to their sales performances in the last 1 year (underperforming sizes are less important)
- Makes sure that sizes that make up X% of the sales are present at store to minimize broken size ranges

### 2.2 Broken Assortment (Size Distribution) Calculation Steps

#### SP Link | SP Rules

- Calculate net units sold at model/color/size level on the country level for the last 12 months.
- Calculate the equivalent sales percentage for S/C/size on the country level using these net units sold in the last 12 months.
- Try to satisfy the size threshold parameter in UI given by the user to complete the size distributions at the destination.

## Step 4: Replenishment Accuracy

The replenishment quantity should ideally align with or slightly exceed the forecast to meet client needs while avoiding overstock or lost sales. Here are some checkpoints to ensure the accuracy of the replenishment;

> Note: Remember that factors like limited warehouse inventory, casepack size, presentation stock, min target, max target, or target modifiers such as min dos, outl, additional lead time etc. also be considered in determining the final replenishment solution.

Compare the average sales over a defined period (e.g., the last 14 days) to the cover period forecast. If the sales are trending upward (seasonality etc.), the forecast should reflect this increase. You should also consider outliers, promo sales, etc. But basically, you can implement a rule that flags significant deviations. (e.g., forecast > 150% of sales or forecast < 50% of sales)

- create_ignore_tables:

Creates tables that will be ignored in the forecasting processes. Table can be in several formats such as Day, Day-Store, Day-Product, Day-ProductGroup. Earthquake happened in February 2023 is an example of ignore table element. Since sales trend in those days are not regular, they eliminated from the process. To add or remove ignore day, changes must be done in `create_ignore_tables` of [liwa noob config](https://github.com/inventanalytics/customer-pipeline-liwa/blob/main/rocks_extension/noob/config.yml).

If we don't see any definition, it means we are using the default. It is not actively used.

Below picture illustrates the Day-Store format ignore day addition from Ebebek.

- daily_data:

Daily data contains sales and inventory position of store-product pairs for each day and all processes run through this table. Main columns of the table are Date-Store-Product-Sales-Inventory. There are also additional column like sales revenue and Usable columns. Sales revenue shows the total revenue gained from store-product for relevant day. Usable column used for forecasting operations. If a date-store-product relation is labeled as not usable(0), this days sales quantity is not used to create forecast. Previously created ignore table affects this column.

Inventory and sales data are received daily. When this table was first created, all historical data was retrieved. Currently, in the daily process, it adds the last day and updates the previous 6 days. If more days need to be updated retrospectively, the update parameter can be adjusted from the config.

The purpose of detecting outlier sales is to identify unexpected sales, thereby improving the accuracy of data analysis and forecast.

# Noob Chain Level

Used for forecasting IA products whereas Noob Daily feeds into RPL and TRN runs.
Since IA pairs do not have historical sales data, results cannot be produced from Lltd. Therefore, an ML-based forecasting model (Prophet) is used. The model is not trained daily; once trained, the coefficients are used daily for predictions. The training is done on a notebook, while the prediction runs daily on a DAG.

- cl_in_season:

Flags whether a product is currently in season by analyzing its sales data.

- cl_weekly_enrich:

Similar to daily data but aggregated on a weekly basis. For more robust forecasts, both input and output (prediction) data are at a weekly level. This approach facilitates easier predictions for products with no historical sales data.

- cl_weekly_inventory:

Weekly inventory data used to create broken assortment data.

- cl_weekly_broken_assortment:

Calculates weekly brokenness ratios.

- cl_weekly_lag_features:

ta.

- cl_weekly_broken_assortment:

Calculates weekly brokenness ratios.

- cl_weekly_lag_features:

Computes sales-related statistics (e.g., total sales, average sales) at different hierarchy levels (product or store) and various lag levels. This allows predictions to be made based on statistics that match the hierarchy of the new product. cl_weekly_lag_features identifies which features are used in the parameter given in the [config](https://github.com/inventanalytics/customer-pipeline-liwa/blob/main/rocks_extension/noob/config.yml).

- cl_weekly_sales_frequency:

Calculates sales frequency at different hierarchy levels for store and product.

- cl_weekly_seasonality_multiplier_features:

Previously, coefficients were calculated at the product-store level on a daily basis. These coefficients are now aggregated to hierarchy and weekly levels for use in CL.

- cl_weekly_forecast_data_prep:

Creates training and test data using the above four tasks.

Creates a table that specify special days which affected the sales trend previously and expected to affect in the future as well. It specify global special days such as Valentines Day as well as the local special days such as Sacrifice Feast.

The holiday information obtained from the customer is read from the config and a holiday table, which Noob will use, is created. (The file is written to invent-liwa-datastore/noob/holidays/)
We transfer the holidays by inserting them into the `create_holiday_table` table in the [config file](https://github.com/inventanalytics/customer-pipeline-liwa/blob/main/rocks_extension/noob/config.yml) . Every year, we need to obtain an updated version of this data from the customer and update it at least once a year. The project team will work on a more systematic solution for this.

### 1- Introduction

In this document, we present the technical details of our Long Term Forecasting (LTF) solution to Liwa. In the document, we first present the customers technical requirements for the long term forecasting problem (Section 2). Then an overview of the algorithm and the technical details of a two-layered model are presented (Section 3). Dag structure of the solution is given in Section 4.

### 2- Long Term Forecasting Problem of Liwa - Customer Requirements

In the LTF problem, Liwa needs to make a decision of next two season's range plans and Open-to-Buy (OTB) requirements. The timing of this planning activity works in the following manner: In December, they finalize projections of the next year's SS season and start preparations for the next year's AW  season. This means at week 45 they need forecasts for the next year's week demand. This means, in their current practice, they need 18 months of demand forecasts.

year's week demand. This means, in their current practice, they need 18 months of demand forecasts.

In their planning activities, Liwa consider section level inventory, profit margin, revenue.

In the current implementation of the product,  we decided to generate a forecast for 12 months. These forecast values are shared with customer weekly basis and utilized in

- open-to-buy (OTB) report
- line-level ORB reports.

Long term forecasting method is designed to work for each (country, brand, section) triplets. In case there is insufficient amount of data for a triplet at section level, the algorithm is designed to consider one level higher. This logic iteratively applied from (country,brand,section) level to the level of a single time series combining all sales.  Different aggregation levels, applied in the product are given in the following table.

g all sales.  Different aggregation levels, applied in the product are given in the following table.

| Aggregation Levels | Combination Components | # of Time Series |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Level 0 | Brand | Section (Pg3) |
| Level 1 | Brand | Section (PG3) |
| Level 2 | Brand | Department (PG2) |
| Level 3 | Brand | Division (PG1) |
| Level 4 | Brand | all |
| Level 5 | all | all |

Level 0 indicates the lowest level that the system generates forecasts. That is also the customers  aggregation level of season planning. From level 0 to level 1, sales of all countries are combined. So, the total number of time series at level is approximately reduced from the multiplication of number of brands, number of countries and number of sections (nb*nc*n3) to the multiplication of brand and section (nb*n3).

### 3- Forecasting Algorithm

In this model, Prophet is considered for capturing trend, seasonality, special day components for each brand, country and section. In addition to these forecast components, effect of brand-specific UDAs are modeled in the system. The effect of UDAs are modeled using LGBM model which is fit to residual values of Prophet model.

### 3.1- Base Model: Prophet for Long Term Forecasting

Base model of the LTF system runs Prophet function of noob at section level. For each (country, brand, section) triplet, historical data of 3 years are obtained from daily table. Then the system generates forecasts with 12 months of horizon.

### 5- Process Flow

The process starts with the noob enrich task. Then for different levels of aggregation, that are explained above, Prophet algorithm is run for a given forecast horizon. Once forecasts at all aggreation levels are generated, they are combined to obtain a forecasted sales for each (brand ,country, section) tuple. The selection algorithm utilizes the availability of the historical data that is explained above .

### 6- Accuracy Metrics

In this project, the predictive accuracy of the forecasting system will be measured using rolling horizon cross validation scheme. In the first round, the first 24 months of data will be used as a training set and sales of months of 25 to 30 will be used as a test set. In the second round, the test data of the first round will be added to the training set and forecasts for the last 30-36 months will be calculated. For these two rounds, the metrics will be used as Key Performance Indicators:

# 1- Introduction

Liwa has a very promotion driven business. Items are launched to stores and online channels with Full Price (first or retail price in our jargon) and they move through phases towards their end of life. First they are transited to Promotion phase and finally to Mark down phase (as shown under following figure). In this stream of the project, our scope is always the items x store clusters (country x price group) which are at promotion phase.

Promotion Forecasting allows Liwa users to get automated forecast projections for the promotion options within defined scope. This solution does not generate suggestions or make a promotion decision for the user. It only produces forecasts on weekly basis and produce results at a report and csv files under file manager.

# 2- Solution Design

## 2.1 Business Requirements & Decision Flow

nd csv files under file manager.

# 2- Solution Design

## 2.1 Business Requirements & Decision Flow

Liwa has many different brands, flagships are lingerie (LAZ, LSI, LSD, LSZ) brands and Gant. Accordingly they have several business teams to lead the planning and allocation of these brands. All these teams have their own budgets of course but in order to manage the overall Liwa business, bottom line aggregated numbers for all brands x categories and options at all different phases are required to be reflected within same report. So during the week, all teams' exercises for all promotion as well as markdown decisions should be gathered to one report called [Executive Summary Report](https://liwa.next.inventanalytics.com/reports/ExecutiveSummary/ExecutiveSummary) to reflect overall picture.

liwa.next.inventanalytics.com/reports/ExecutiveSummary/ExecutiveSummary) to reflect overall picture.

Promotion decisions are made at category x country x price group level. Our forecasts are produced at [option x country x price group] level and then aggregated to different levels of categories depending on the regarding Brands way of working and decision making.

We can consider that the so called base hierarchyis [Brand x Division x Department x Section x Core/Fashion x Class]. A brand can choose make their promotion decisions at various different levels depending on the category, and that decision applies to all options under that category, of course for options at Promotion phase(explained in the introduction section).

- For example LAZ brands BRAS division decision are made at DEPARTMENT level, but LINGERIE division decision are made at SECTION level.

ion decision are made at DEPARTMENT level, but LINGERIE division decision are made at SECTION level.

## 2.2 Solution Design Details

## 2.2 Solution Design Details

Promotion forecast solution gathers systemic data, and regular user inputs in order to provide forecasts. User inputs are uploaded via [File Manager](https://liwa.next.inventanalytics.com/upload-management/file-manager) UIs and results are provided to the client using a set of reports ([Aggregate Promo Report](https://liwa.next.inventanalytics.com/reports/AggregatePromoReport/PromoAggregation) and Executive Summary Report). There are no OMEGAor ACMEimplementation. For forecasting, noob chain level weeklydag is implemented. System also saves csv outputs (which is the input data of Aggregate Promo Report) under file manager.

### 2.2.1 Output

### 2.2.1 Output

Promotion forecasts are produced at [option x country x price group x promotion name] on weekly basis for a span of 1 week. Output is provided on Monday but the forecast covers the seven days from Wednesday to Tuesday. When run every three hours, gathers the most recent item-sale-list option x country x price group tags (FP, PM, MDP, MD) and filter is applied to only show PM tagged items. In this report a user can make their selections at any category hierarchy level so it serves to every brand according to their needs. After they do their selections, they import the data at option x country x price group x promotion name level and put to a folder. All users' inputs are combined together and showed together at Executive Summary Report. Throughout a week, at every run happening every three hours during a day, new user files is added on top of the compilation. Z added theirs after 6 hours, BIZs results are added on top of the previous inputs from other users. This report only shown for the must up-to-date data updates.

In this report, along with all promotion types provided in the DNA file, one additional forecast current promotion is provided. Currently client is sending us the promotion data but unfortunately the promotion names are not standard, also the data is not very reliable. So current promotion forecast is the forecast which is calculated assuming the exact same promotion will continue this week. This is done via calculating the current weeks discount rate through sales datas revenue asp vs price data. More on this at the algorithm section.

#### 2.2.5.2 Executive Summary Report

This report is designed to gather all promo user decisions, add first price items' forecasts along with Monday mark-down results in order to show the whole businesses KPIs all at the same page & place. Every new selection for promotions, as well as changes made to item-sale-list are effected to this report. This report only shown for the must up-to-date data updates.

If a selection for promotion type is not made for a category, then it is assumed to remain same and current promotion information is brought to the report.

For First Price (FP) tagged items also current promotion forecasts are brought. We expect the discount rate to be zero for these but sometimes this does not hold.

The reporting workflow Databricks job is named [Phase 2 Flow  Data Upload](https://adb-4437560677036038.18.azuredatabricks.net/jobs/803501600182080?o=4437560677036038). Sale List and Promo User Decisions update tasks use input files read via Data Upload UI.

677036038). Sale List and Promo User Decisions update tasks use input files read via Data Upload UI.

Data Upload UI triggers to receive the latest files are initiated at 06:45, 09:45, 12:45, 15:45 UTC+4, UAE time zone every weekday. Reporting workflows begin 30 minutes after these triggers as 30-minute-long buffers are sufficient for writing the data from Cheetah to Azure Blob Container. Within this buffer time, API calls will be retried on failure and an email will be sent on multiple failures.

CX-IT team manages the API calls and there is a parameter called *startDate* which allows the API to return files uploaded to the system after that timestamp. Each scheduled API call for new files will input the timestamp of the latest successful API call as the *startDate* so that only the recently uploaded files are returned to the Azure Blob.

I call as the *startDate* so that only the recently uploaded files are returned to the Azure Blob.

Under the directory *invent-liwa-datastore/ui-data/data_upload*, folders for each API call from Cheetah are visible with call ids beginning with their timestamps.

Under each folder, there are folders for the defined data types to be uploaded.

Under each of these folders, there is *status.json* file indicating the status of the API call. If there has been a new file uploaded from that data type since the last trigger, there will be a *result/* folder with csv file(s) in it. Even if there are multiple files uploaded by the client, they may be unioned in a simple file named *part1.csv*. There can be multiple of these *partX.csv* files depending on how large the uploaded files are.

Sale List and Promotion User Decisions are now used as delta tables instead of the csv files in file manager.

and Promotion User Decisions are now used as delta tables instead of the csv files in file manager.

To track which data upload files were already processed by the reporting workflow, a delta table is used under path */mnt/invent-liwa-datastore/reporting/liwa_data_upload_ui_logs/.*This log table includes *folder_name*, *data_type*, *timestamp* to keep the information regarding which data type from which folder has been previously upserted to the delta tables. Note that the timestamp in this table indicates the time when the files were read by the reporting workflow, not when they were read from Cheetah.

s the time when the files were read by the reporting workflow, not when they were read from Cheetah.

Tasks for [Sale List](https://adb-4437560677036038.18.azuredatabricks.net/editor/notebooks/2369610441592581?o=4437560677036038) and [Promo User Decisions](https://adb-4437560677036038.18.azuredatabricks.net/editor/notebooks/4425738002387532?o=4437560677036038) both read the logs file to find which folders from API calls are not yet processed and collect the files from them. Any duplications are resolved via keeping the latest arriving row for the item x store cluster pair. Files from Data Upload UI (*partX.csv*) also include timestamps from when the rows were uploaded to the UI screen so that the latest row can be selected using the timestamp column.

Clients promotion data is not clean, as in the type of promotion can not be introduced to the model as it is not governed in a structured way. Promotion names are entered manually and even though a historic study can be made, future data will still be bad and would be useless. So we have used average sales price in sales data and retail price data to understand the actual discount amount for any option x country x price group  at any given week. We know that promotions are applied at category level so this helped us fill the NA values for a pair when they actually has no sales. We have introduced the calculated discount rates and built a model around discount rate. In order to create forecasts for the future, we have converted every promotion type to a discount rate. Some of the promotions are already discount rates so they are naturally used. For BxGy like promotions (e.g. B1G1), a rough estimate with expected effect is determined by expert opinion.

like promotions (e.g. B1G1), a rough estimate with expected effect is determined by expert opinion.

Another case is price points (e.g. 3 for 349). For such cases, an average price for a unit is calculated. Every week when algorithm runs, related categories inventory weighted price is calculated and by using unit price  / average category price we calculate a discount rate for these as well.

All of this promotion options' discount mappings as well as unit prices (which are used every week to calculate the discount rate at that week) is available at `/mnt/invent-liwa-datastore/promotion/promotion_options_prepared.csv`

## 3.2 Forecast Horizon

According the business flow, client usually makes their decisions by Tuesday or Wednesday and they expect the forecast to cover one week from Wednesday to Tuesday. So a forecast is calculated on Monday to cover days ahead. Our weekly forecast capabilities are not able to produce results starting by a weekday other than Monday so we are currently sending the client an adjusted weekly forecast. Our forecast produce results which starts at Monday but we adjust the special day features (bring future special days if there is any) as if the calculated weekdays covers from Wed to Tue. Extension task explains that is done here more in detail.

## 3.3 Elasticity Post Process

The approach used here is same as it is done in Famous Footwear Caleres project.

icity Post Process

The approach used here is same as it is done in Famous Footwear Caleres project.

The primary objective of this extension is to refine forecasts for new scenarios by incorporating different promotional strategies and discount levels.

These adjustments are based on the forecast data of pairs that currently have active promotions. By leveraging elasticity coefficients, the extension applies a lower bound of -1.5 and an upper bound of -4, ensuring that an increase of 10% in the discount rate results in a projected sales increase of at least 15%, with a potential maximum increase of 40%.

This documentation presents a unified explanation of the allocation process followed jointly by Invent.ai  and Liwa. It outlines the shared practices as well as the differences between internal and client-side documentation to ensure full alignment and process clarity.

1. Scope File Ownership & Purpose (Aligned)

The Scope File is the foundational input for the allocation system, enabling the distribution of products to designated stores and warehouses. It is maintained by the Brand Team and Branch Merchandiser at Liwa and must be saved in the shared directory by 6:00 a.m. daily. Invent then processes this file to execute the allocation according to the plan.

2. Scope File Format (Differences Noted)

While both sides utilize a scope file, Liwas format includes specific fields such as GRN  date, RDD , and an 'Allocate from GCC' indicator.

Internally, *Invents system interprets allocation types through structured input mappings like option-store or option-warehouse pairs.*

3. Allocation Types (Aligned)

Both documents define the following three allocation types:

- Heres how the allocation type is determined from the option-store/warehouse pairs in the scope file:

---

 How[Invent.ai](http://Invent.ai)Determines the Allocation Type from Input Pairs

[Invent.ai](http://Invent.ai) uses the structure of the scope filespecifically the combination of option-store or option-warehouse pairs and their respective start datesto determine the allocation type. Heres a breakdown of the logic:

---

1. Regional Allocation

Definition: Allocation from a *local warehouse* to *stores within the same country*.

How its detected:

metadata.title: Unified Allocation Process Documentation  Invent.ai  & Liwa (To Be Shared)

content:
nition: Allocation from a *local warehouse* to *stores within the same country*.

How its detected:

- The store and its assigned warehouse are in the same country.
- Only store codes are listed in the scope (no intermediate GCC warehouse is explicitly involved).
- The warehouse assignment is determined by the PDSR file, which defines the store-warehouse mapping.
- No abroad allocation logic is needed.

Key signal:

 The system sees a store that maps to a local warehouse via the PDSR and no cross-country date-based behavior is defined.

---

1. Abroad - Direct Allocation

Definition: Products are shipped *directly* from the UAE warehouse to stores in GCC countries. A small buffer may be sent to the local warehouse.

How its detected:

metadata.title: Unified Allocation Process Documentation  Invent.ai  & Liwa (To Be Shared)

content:
e to stores in GCC countries. A small buffer may be sent to the local warehouse.

How its detected:

- The same allocation date is provided for both:
- The GCC warehouse and
- The GCC countrys stores
- This indicates that stock is not waiting at the warehouseits going straight from UAE to stores, while the warehouse just receives a replenishment buffer.

Key signal:

 Both warehouse and store for a GCC region appear in the scope file with the same start date.

---

1. Abroad - Stepwise Allocation

Definition: Products move from UAE  GCC warehouse, then from GCC warehouse  stores.

How its detected:

- A GCC warehouse is listed in the scope file with an earlier allocation date than its associated stores.
- This means the warehouse receives the goods first, then stores are replenished later from that GCC warehouse.

Key signal:

 The warehouse start date is earlier than the store start date for the same product.

---

4. Run Mechanism (Aligned)

---

4. Run Mechanism (Aligned)

The allocation process operates through two main modes, both using the same underlying DAG: `adhoc_allocation_run`.

- Initial Allocation  This mode runs automatically once per day based on the daily scope file. It is triggered by the forecasting pipeline after data preparation is complete.
- Ad-hoc Allocation  This is a manually triggered process via the user interface. It provides flexibility for non-scheduled allocation needs such as reallocation or late stock arrivals.

5. Abroad Allocation Logic (Aligned with Clarified Handling)

The handling of cross-border allocations is aligned, with both documents recognizing two sub-types: Direct and Stepwise.

metadata.title: Unified Allocation Process Documentation  Invent.ai  & Liwa (To Be Shared)

content:
s-border allocations is aligned, with both documents recognizing two sub-types: Direct and Stepwise.

- If the warehouse and store allocation dates are identical, the process is considered a Direct Allocation, and the product is shipped from the UAE warehouse to both the GCC store and warehouse.
- If the warehouse allocation date is earlier than the store date, it is treated as a Stepwise Allocation. The product first goes to the GCC warehouse, then to the stores. Invent ensures a replenishment buffer is included when transferring stock to the warehouse.

Promotion module runs within chain_level_promotion dag, which runs after noob_etl within the daily dag. Within  chain_level_promotion dag, there is an external databricks job workflow called `chain_level_promotion_prod` which is triggered during the daily dag run.

While client expects the results weekly on Mondays, our dag runs 7 days a week within the daily dag, after wait_noob_etl dag. In practice, we only provide results of Monday morning, and we save the output to another back-up location for the days other than Monday.
